Inflation in Europe has slowed down on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the European Community Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
The official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, "said Bloomberg.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leading interest rate by saying that the decline in interest, with the growth of raw materials prices and the decline in unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to an analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "inflation must be discouraged" in order to no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later stage.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 per cent has been a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
Cereal term market ratings have increased by 88 per cent and soybean prices have also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 per cent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 per cent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the master rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly in early December. Thus, since 2002, it has currently had the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never previously seen such low socialist support, that is, 13 per cent.
For faithful voters, the difference would represent more than two-thirds (71 per cent) of support for a fifth (20 per cent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party) due to the greater determination of the opposition voters.
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two per cent throughout the population.
Of the faithful voters some to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 per cent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been so high, it is 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent complements the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population is planning to worsen and only a tenth is planning to improve the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, that is, a majority never seen in Gallup's previous surveys, found that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather wrong than well.
13 percent of the respondents have confidence or much confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the President of the Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be treated without change of government.
While after last October's riots, 35 per cent of the respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
To the question about the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly go to vote and the 20 per cent additional said that they would probably go to vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to hold next Sunday," only 55 per cent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the outcome of the referendum would not be doubtful.
74 per cent of people would say no to the fees for higher education, 79 per cent would say no to the cost of consultation and 84 per cent would say no to the cost of staying in the hospital.
When we look at only the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital travel costs.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost 20 percent
The hypermarkets in Budaörs' commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Panier also increased by 16 per cent on average, a value increase well above a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
The prices, "which had already fled" in the major food stores last December, no longer increased sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily Panier in the sonded hypermarkets has exceeded at least 91 forints, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and living fish remained almost at last year's level, but the prices of turkey net, nuts and poppy increased sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but at Auchan, one kilo of bread was found only 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the registered bottle of two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it was only 257 forints of the recorded bottle included.
It only prevents this year, in terms of Panier daily, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the least expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily Panier by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing the most expensive basket of last year with the cheapest basket of this year, we see a 12 percent difference while the difference between the cheapest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate had already been noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process made trade perplexed, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin applied to products so long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader poorly calculates the rotation of a product, it may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to trade intensity.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily Panier prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1 720 forints higher than the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was higher than last year's 1 630 forints and the prices of the least expensive increased by 1 284 forints as well.
By reconciling the two Christmas seasons, we have seen a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumption items have increased by more than 30 per cent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some of the basic needs, the Statistical Institute has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, for flour and egg.)
According to Panier's daily Panier, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 per cent from the base.
The evidence suggests that flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to have the sharp price increase also accepted by multinational companies.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-standing food by pallets.
Wednesday morning important tails were formed in the three hypermarkets because the number of customers has increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumption items.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly due to the incorrect use of antibiotics, were registered in hospitals.
The health conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overcrowding of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago a MRSA infection was diagnosed at the János Hospital's traumatology service.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on an hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred at the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after he had to return because of a MRSA infection and since then, the doctors have not been able to do a significant operation because of the bacterium in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multiresistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multiresistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people are wearing Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angines, amygdalites, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily healable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which react well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant antibiotic bacteria that will rapidly proliferate under bad hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, on elderly patients, small weight or with weakened organism.
According to the director of János Hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of hospital daily.
Above all, infection with the epidemic should not be confused, MRSA is not found only where it is not sought, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SA resists antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the caring staff put rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carrying MRSA, however infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not in mode
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multiresistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection is particularly evident in hospitals and in elderly residences, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these reviews.
Most cases only occur if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor of the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes are also in place.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological levies are even more rare in ambulatory care and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferates from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, put gloves and protective masks. However, significant gaps are detected in hospitals also in this field.
MRSA proliferates by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemic, patients should be removed from each other by a minimum of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is less manifestable or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is exorbitant expenditure for social security funds, which is why it is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multiresistant pathogens (such as MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, who was responsible for a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official finding concerning the fatal accident caused by the 22nd district commissioner was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the 22nd district commissioner, resigned from his post since, who crashed a pedestrian by provoking his death last Tuesday, would have led to drunkenness or dizziness, said Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the Capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which already found that the former Commissioner had not used alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd district police station crashed a 55-year-old man who was in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, on Kossuth Lajos Street of the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian passage.
(In fact, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian passage is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Road Code a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and asked for his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident has greatly affected him.
The investigation of this case is carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office for Investigations.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the outset with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Finance Minister, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest with a total value of EUR 400 million on a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit contract of EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The agreement on the €150 million credit also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later, following the extension of the credit contract.
The parties have signed a EUR 50 million contract for innovation, and the state budget will use this envelope first as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
In the negotiations, the draft of line 4 of the subway was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would rediscuss the possible amendment of the original contract once Hungary had finalised the details of the financing of the subway with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB shall grant its appropriations in accordance with the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
Bulgaria, EU real estate market paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans, which has not been mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market that is always the cheapest but will become expensive quickly?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re / Max.
At present, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most envisioned target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses by the cheap sea.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Sables d'or," the "Sun Coast," the old Sozopol and Nessebar, but they are increasingly looking for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to Re / Max Bulgaria's analysts, sooner or later, the central region of the country, Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, commercial and office surfaces promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of Europe's most attractive golf havens and thus to be a priority destination, after the summer and winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors already buy in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time seeking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English, but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. At the edge of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski stations, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, said Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re / Max Bulgaria.
The people who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price of between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dashed houses, at a price of between 5 and 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication opportunities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed as one of the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who purchase in the hope of achieving a medium or long-term surplus value.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly increasing as a result of a growing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, over the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices mainly exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication from Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of professionals end Tuesday, yet Wednesday, after the official opening, the ministers' negotiations on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At this time, strong discussions are being held on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss accurate figures, but was ready to sign an agreement on the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent from the 1990 level until 2020.
Another important subject of the conference is whether developed countries are committed, apart from emission reduction, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement has also been signed on the aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a Board of Directors of 16 members probably under the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to continue its role as an admiral ship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 from the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement," and was ready to reduce them to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and / or developing countries were also ready to make commitments that were appropriate to their responsibility and capacity.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the Kyoto Protocol countries had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time made 8 per cent less commitment.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent from the level of the period 1985-1987, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international climate policy agreement must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which has been highlighted in the new report of IPCC, the international scientific body, which has obtained the United Nations Nobel Peace Prize, to deal with climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
The British Army units communicate on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of making themselves popular.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has been passionate about YouTube: the special units in Afghanistan are loading video sequences on operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londrès or the compatriots load them over the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net by this way and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered itself as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were placed on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way does not cost much to the usual television-based recruitment advertisements, which have been communicated to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably bears a political message as it justifies in a special form the suitability of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is bothered because, apart from carefully designed and composted videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in "official" propaganda films, a little hypocrites, officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos were already on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army has been working for the loading of these videos only recently.
The Americans are recruiting a little differently by using the American's Army's shootout game downloadable for free. In this game, the player can get directly into the place of the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
