The mega-strike forces come together
The League trade unions and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form their strike commission on Friday to coordinate the indefinite strike of Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the law on health funds, the strike will begin.
This will certainly result in significant traffic closures as rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and BKV's employees (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The League Syndicates will make known, Friday afternoon, the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The LIGA - MOSZ strike commission will also be set up and will serve as the coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and, from Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work for an indeterminate period if they fail to reach agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in Parliament on the law on health funds, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Cards Act, the trade unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide on what action to take.
On Monday's agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the Health Cards Act will only take place late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, large traps are planned in the traffic: the railways will stop work for an indeterminate period and during the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are at risk of being arrested.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the track will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strike, and their list is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report making the strike for an indeterminate period, others reported a temporary stop to work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trade Union of Cheminots (VDSZSZ) have failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, or, as the Christmas parties approach, more and more are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the League's Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Union will strike four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union called for a strike for 2 a.m. and 2 p.m. to 8 p.m, respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike all over the country in alternance, the Health and Social Sector Employees Union (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will conduct a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four claims made by the League requires the government to withdraw its proposal for health reform and to put a new approach to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be put in place from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim wants a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, that would allow the system to pass on the functions that deserve it before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Trade Union of Cheminots (VDSZSZ), attached to the Union of the League, of the proposal by the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased the risk country
According to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, established last August, with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for Better Hungary), in several aspects, increases the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning," the company notes that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur following the worsening ethnic tension already existing between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary."
The research institute added that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to cause this situation to be the main reason.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings who have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians."
The problem is worsened, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened, and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, due to the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular with regard to the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country."
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganization of the Hungarian radical and extreme right groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, giving the name of "national self-defence association."
"The common feature of these assemblies is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their members to defence missions (disasters, national defence, law enforcement), armed if necessary, by referring to the inaptitude of the police, the army, in other words of the state," they added.
They reported that everything was going on according to the method which, based on the ransom of the political society and the parties, seeks to taste different political ambitions from a civil point of view.
