A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen's Nazi archives, which trace the destiny of 17.5 million victims of the Hitlerian regime, are free of access.
The 47 million archives, stored over 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. in an individual and nominative manner, on the request of a former victim or his or her right holders.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research "including the movement of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the public opening of these nominative documents due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by Gestapo had been collected after war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subject to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said in 2006 Dr. Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische Universität in Berlin.
