Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind pears with poles, like those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning on Venus.
The European "Venus Express" probe today has provided proof of this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus breaks out at about 56 kilometres of cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature."
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have revealed life on Earth: thunderstorms would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If there has been a life, it must have been at a very old date of history," says Sean Solomon of the "Carnegie Institution" in Washington.
There should now be little living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about 100 times more dense than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin," Russel said.
Why Venus, which is so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, since no more probe was on the way for the exploration of this planet since the eighties.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more than supposed to be at first.
As a result, the researchers found, in addition to the wind peatlands already known at the North Pole, a peaty of clouds at the South Pole, which is turning much faster.
The phenomenon recalls air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12.100 kilometres, almost as large.
The planet called an evening or morning star turns around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, does not recall the Earth, scientists assume that both planets have formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has set on Earth as carbonate, it is on Venus most of the atmosphere.
