It's not Warhols' boxes.
The one who connects Sweden's concepts with wood box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden put shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the eighty-ten "Type Stockholm" Brillo-Boxs listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxs of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today results in a disenchantor result: the six "Brillo-Boxes," whose former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum made a gift in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large part of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm," which are circulating on the international art market.
Ancient history is encircled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created its first "Brillo-Boxes," painted wood boxes in New York, based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - hundreds of cardboard Brillo boxes: These were not from (for financial reasons) Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cartonnage factory.
These were not works of art here, but rather their models, exposure samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wood boxes produced in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time today talk about about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered law into the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol allowed, with the name "Type Stockholm."
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum mistakenly claimed that about 100 wooden boxes had been produced and exposed in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have given him.
In fact, the 105 Hulten boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
On that date, Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservative of the Moderna Museet, examined three other Swedish private collections, including two made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and punctured, then applied with a white oil paint brush.
The texture of the copies that date from 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a background layer on stratified panels, using a roller of paint - in addition, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official Brillo-Boxes list," says Moderna Museet's director, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will clasten the six boxes in his collection as copies / exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powder soap boxes.
But since then we have had an inexorable silence over there.
